article.description: Chandi Jones scored a career-high 17 points and the Minnesota Lynx hung on to beat the Houston Comets 73-62 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Loss puts Comets behind Storm in West race
article.linkText: Jones scores 17 to lead Lynx past Comets
article.story:
MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- Chandi Jones scored a career-high 17 points
and the Minnesota Lynx hung on to beat the Houston Comets 73-62
Tuesday night.

Minnesota, which helped its postseason chances with the victory,
also got 16 points from Nicole Ohlde and 14 from Svetlana
Abrosimova.

"We knew this was a very important game for us to try and stay
alive," Jones said. "We came up big tonight and played really
well with each other and didn't give up."

The Lynx (14-16) remained one game behind fourth-place Phoenix,
and moved a half-game ahead of Los Angeles in the Western
Conference with four games remaining.

Houston (16-14) dropped a half-game behind idle Seattle in the
race for second place in the conference and home court in the first
round of the playoffs. The Comets have lost four straight on the
road.

"This is one of the most disappointing losses I've ever been
in," Houston coach Van Chancellor said.

Up by four at intermission, Minnesota, which had lost seven of
its previous nine games, used good ball movement to score the first
nine points of the second half to take a 47-34 lead.

"We talk about how in the first five minutes of the second half
we had to take it strong," said Abrosimova, who finished the run
with a layup during a 2-on-1 with Jones. "Today I felt like we
played smart."

However, the Lynx have a penchant for letting second-half leads
get away -- doing so in four of their previous six losses. Tuesday
was no exception.

Houston went on a 9-0 run, including seven points by Sheryl
Swoopes, to cut the deficit to 53-51. A pair of free throws by
Swoopes gave the Comets a 57-56 advantage with 6:28 remaining. But
Houston didn't lead again.

"When we got a one-point lead we ought to find a way to win,
but we didn't," Chancellor said, walking away from reporters
shaking his head.

A layup, short hook and two free throws by Ohlde put Minnesota
up 64-60 with 4:19 remaining. Houston did not score in the final
3:23.

Tamika Williams was one of three Lynx players with six rebounds.
She grabbed two after free throw misses to keep the ball away from
Houston in the final two minutes.

Swoopes finished with 21 points, Michelle Snow had 17 and Janeth
Arcain added 10 for the Comets, who will play Phoenix at home
Thursday.

Minnesota, 3-11 on the road, plays its next three away from home
including at Phoenix and Los Angeles.

"We know how difficult it is to win on the road," Minnesota
coach Suzie McConnell Serio said. "We will be playing teams that
we are going head-to-head with for a playoff spot. We're not
putting any pressure on ourselves. We're looking at it as an
opportunity."
